column168: Avon, IN-06/03/2021-LTCX1940- Argon, Refrigerated Liquid  On 06/03/2021, at 2130 hrs, personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered LTCX 1940, a loaded tank car of Argon, Refrigerated Liquid, leaking from normal venting relief valve vent and valve cabinet. The car was isolated and (Linde Inc., NRC, IDEM and were notified.  CHEMTREC Report # 2021-060300364. RMS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car venting from the normal venting relief valve vent and valve cabinet. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Michael Bolton 716-435-1606. Contractor personnel opened the cabinet housing and observed ice fall from the valve and the normal venting valve reset and the leak stopped and the product that fell to the ground evaporated quickly so there was no remediation cleanup. The leak was secured by RMS and a Linde Inc. Technician and the car was released for transport pending an OTMA1. This incident did require a special switching move. 7.1 is required.  Cause Code: 702 NARRI: 2

column168: During a truck to truck transfer at Veolia's 10 day in-transit facility in Henderson, CO, a container was identified as leaking due a container failure.  Upon further investigation it was determined that the original shipper of the material did not use the proper type of packaging for the material that was shipped.
column169: Although the leaking container was not showing signs of leaking prior to shipping, as a best practice, Veolia employees were retrained on Veolia's procedure for container inspections prior to shipment.  Additionally, Veolia informed the shipper of the incident and has suspended picking up this type of material up in the future.  Veolia also supplied the generator with a copy of the applicable DOT regulation for proper packaging guidance.

column168: Consignment arrived into RDU on May 19. Customs Border Protection screened on Jun 3 and advised station of denial of entry.  During the inspection of air waybill 006-44026032, 20.25 liters of an unregistered pesticide (DDVP Sniper) was found concealed within food items contained in this shipment.  When CBP referred this pesticide to the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), they refused it.  Based on EPA’s refusal, and the evidence that some of the pesticide containers leaked into the dried leaves concealing them, the entire shipment must be re-exported.  Please see the attached CBP Form 4647.  To the best of my knowledge, all of the pesticides have been removed from the food items and placed into two boxes.  These boxes will need to be properly labeled (the manufacturer states this pesticide to be toxic and flammable) and checked for leakage prior to transport.  I double bagged the bottles exhibiting obvious signs of leakage.  The prohibited items that I previously removed for destruction will be returned to the shipment for re-export tomorrow.  I notified the consignee, Mr. Azubuike Amadi, on June 3, 2021.  If you have any questions, please contact me at 919-674-3415.

column168: At 11:48 EST - ERTS was contacted by John Shaleen (TransWood Carriers) regarding a NA1993 diesel fuel spill that occurred in soil and on concrete.  The spill is located at the customer's site - "Breezy Ace Hardware" - 8170 County Rd 11 - Breezy Points, MN. Transwood has requested a contractor out for cleanup and containment. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor who arrived on site and estimated that approximately 65 gallons of NA1993 released to an area of concrete and migrated to an area of soil. No drains or waterways were impacted by this release. The environmental contractor reported that a hose popped off drop fitting resulting in the release. The environmental contractor utilized hand tools and granular absorbents to clean the impacted concrete. The environmental contractor utilized hand tools to remove the impacted area of soil and obtain sampling for laboratory analysis. All waste was containerized and taken off site for pending disposal.

column168: Report on the TILX 110101 tank car leak in Lock Haven, Pa Date: 6/10/2021 Reported at: 10:17AM Summary: An Inspector from the Pennsylvania Public Utility Commission (PUC) was doing a spot check inspection on hazmat cars located in the yard at Lock Haven. He discovered a leaking tank car that was venting a small amount of hydrochloric acid from the top of the car around the valve area. The PUC Inspector notified General Manager at the Bellefonte office that there was an issue with the car. The GM then notified Operations about the issue. Operations STO then responded to Lock Haven to observe the tank car and relieve responsibility from the PUC Inspector for keeping anyone from getting near or injured from the leaking car. The STO took control of the situation once he arrived on the scene from the inspector at that point. While the STO was enroute, the Superintendent was in contact with Univar which is responsible for this loaded car since it was not delivered to PVS, which is where the car was destined for. The Superintendent was able to confirm that North Shore Railroad would need to contact a remediation company to deal with this incident as Univar did not have a response team for such incidents anymore and contacted Enviroserve which was the old Northridge Group we used in the past to deal with hazardous material incidents. He was able to get Enviroserve to dispatch a crew to respond almost immediately from Winfield to Lock Haven. While Enviroserve was responding, the STO  applied track protection to track 5 in Lock Haven for the responding crew.  Enviroserve did respond within an hour and a half to the location at Lock Haven to begin sizing up the situation and begin correction of the issue with the car. Enviroserve’s crew was on scene for about 1 hour and 45 mintues from the time of arrival to the time of departure. Enviroserve corrected the loose bolts that held the vapor housing valve onto the car. It was the bottom flange bolts for the valve that were discovered to be loose. Enviroserve tightened three of the bolts which needed at least ¼ turn to snug up. The fourth bolt needed to be tightened at least ½ a turn to snug up. After the housing was tighten up, Enviroserve then cleaned the outside of the car to remove any residual hydrochloric acid from the outside skin of the car to prevent any injury. It was then agreed that the situation was remediated. After the response crew cleared the track, and the STO then removed the track protection. Both Enviroserve and the STO both left the scene shortly thereafter back for their respective terminals. The GM was contacted by the STO that the issue was resolved and to let him know to keep an eye on the car on future movements to make sure there are no other leaks are discovered with this car.   Response and arrival times: Notified of incident 10:17 HR Supervisor of Train Ops (STO) response to Lock Haven 10:30 HR Supervisor of Train Ops (STO) arrived in Lock Haven 11:25 HR Enviroserve arrived on scen

column168: 6-6-2021 09:30  Slick Response received a call from Kirk Higbie with PTRA stating that he had a chemical odor located at their Manchester Yard, and asked that I respond to the yard and try to find the car. He stated that they had chemical cars spotted around track 8.  10:15   Slick personnel are on location at this time. After meeting with PTRA rep, we began walking between tracks until the odor was located. Upon locating the odor on empty/residue car number DOWX 34008, Slick personnel gained clearance to climb the car and investigate the cause. After opening the protective housing, I noticed that you could hear air escaping from inside the car around valves. After checking both valves, all bolts on both valves were extremely loose with four bolts with approx .25 inches gap between the nut and the flange. After tightening all the bolts on the valves, there was no more odor coming from the car. At this point, I checked all other bolts and found them to be tightened so we resealed the protective housing and notified Kirk of the findings. Track was released and placed back into service. 12:30   Slick personnel have released the car back in service at this time. 13:30   Slick personnel are parked, and equipment has been placed back into service  Seal # 009549

column168: On Sunday June 6th, 2021 at 2000hrs Mr. Kirk Higbie with Port Terminal Railroad Association contacted M&M Emergency and Environmental Services (M&M) and requested assistance with a leaking railcar loaded with Methanol. The leaking car GATX36400 had been isolated at the PTRA Pasadena Yard Rail Yard on Track #4. M&M’s emergency response personnel arrived at 2030hrs and begin an assessment of the car. Visual observations indicated a steady flow of Methanol leaking from under the protective dome housing on top of the car. M&M’s Hazmat Team climbed onto the car, opened the protective housing dome lid and observed the 3inch (”) Stainless Steel liquid valve to be in the full open position. Methanol was observed leaking from the 3” valve up through the threads around the 3” Stainless Steel plug. Hazmat Team members closed the 3” liquid valve and the leak immediately stopped. The 3” plug accompanying the valve was checked and found “not” wrench tight. The plug was tightened and secured. M&M personnel stood by and verified that no further leaks were found. To assure a safe and secure load M&M requested the railcar be moved to a siding until daylight to verify that all leaks were repaired. On June 7th, 2021 at 0900hrs. M&M personnel rechecked GATX36400 and verified that there were no active leaks. Mr. Higbie was notified that GATX36400 was releasable for shipment. No further actions were required.

Due to the hazard that the material presented, the packaging specifications could not be safely obtained.

column168: A Safety-Kleen Systems Sales and Service Representative the aforementioned drum into the company's transportation network. The drum was transported to the Safety-Kleen facility located in Springdale, AR. where the drum was placed in 10 Day storage. Springdale, AR. experienced a uptick in temperature causing the warehouse to become much warmer that than when the drum was originally placed. The drum became pressurized due to the heat and the gasket between the open-top lid and the upper drum shoulder failed resulting in the material leaking and running down the drum creating a very small pool of material on the pallet on which the drum sat and the warehouse floor. The cause of the release was found to be from lack of head space in the drum. This leak was discovered during a daily facility walk conducted every morning. The closure ring on the drum was torqued stopping the release. The drum and area affected by the release was remediated by warehouse personnel.
column169: Safety-Kleen Systems management contacted the generator and discussed the necessity of proper head space left in drums. The management team will re-iterate the importance of container inspections prior to accepting drums / containers into our transportation network. Sales and Service Reps will refer to drum closure instructions for the relative brand of drum and check all closures to ensure they are to specification according to the closure instructions.

column168: On 6/4/21 at 0230 ET, residual UN1824, Sodium Hydroxide, 8, PGII was discovered on the trailer floor at a travel stop. Landstar retained ERTS who retained Lincoln Environmental to perform cleanup activities. Upon the contractor's arrival to the site, the cargo was assessed. After removing 8 out of the 13 pallets, one (1) 30 - gallon poly drum was discovered to be crushed and leaking due to a load shift. The contractor estimated that approximately 4 gallons of product released impacting the trailer floor. The damaged drum was overpacked into one (1) 55 - gallon poly. Lincoln Environmental then utilized granular absorbents and and absorbent pads to decontaminate the impacted trailer floor and adjacent cargo. The spent absorbents were placed into the 55 - gallon drum with the damaged 30 - gallon drum. The contractor then departed the site with the waste generated.

IN THE DMP, PACKAGE WAS OPENED AND FOUND TO CONTAIN, FOUR, 1 GALLON, PLASTIC JUGS OF CITRUS ASSAULT, CITRUS BASED ALL PURPOSE DEGREASER, BEING SHIPPED AS A CORROSIVE HAZMAT, (CORROSIVE LIQUID, BASIC, INORAGANIC, N.O.S. RELOAD SUPERVISOR WAS MADE AWARE OF A PACKAGE SPILLING. THE LIQUID WAS SMOKING SLIGHTLY WHEN IT CONTACTED THE METAL SLIDE ON DOOR 6 AND IT WAS EMITTING AN IRRITATING ODOR. HE MADE THE CENTER MANAGER AWARE AND THE CENTER MANAGER CALLED ME, ASKING TO INVESTIGATE AS THE LOCAL SORT HAZMAT RESPONDER WAS NO LONGER ON SITE. I WENT TO THE CENTER AND INVESTIGATED THE SPILLAGE, DETERMINED THE PACKAGE WAS LIKELY AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT, AND RESPONDED APPROPRIATELY, USING THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET AS A GUIDE. I CLEANED UP THE SPILL IN THE TRAILER AND ON THE SLIDE, TRANSPORTED THE DAMAGED PACKAGES TO THE PROCESSING AREA, AND PROCESSED ALL THE DAMAGED ITEMS.

column168: On June 23, 2021, personnel at the R+L Carriers (RLC) terminal located at the above-referenced address observed a cargo leak in trailer LE3221 located at dock door 81. Upon further inspection, one (1) 5-gallon pail of UN1263 polyester resin was damaged by a forklift and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement underneath the trailer. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from Hazmat Special Services (HSS) to perform the necessary corrective action. HSS personnel drummed the damaged pail and utilized absorbents to remediate the impacted surface.

column168: On 6/08/2021 there was a large leak from the bottom of a 55 gallon metal drum on the back of a Veolia trailer located at Norlite, LLC in Cohoes, NY. The truck/trailer arrived at the Norlite location from the Veolia, Schenectady, NY location. Liquid was observed coming out the back of the trailer upon arrival in the parking lot at the Norlite facility. The Veolia driver was notified of the leak by Norlite employees and he immediately notified Veolia. The Veolia safety manager and NYDEC were notified of the spill by the Veolia driver. Clean up operations were performed by trained Veolia employees.    Upon inspecting the trailer, employees found debris under the drum that caused the drum to be punctured. It was assumed the leak started on the way into the Norlite facility due to the rough road entering the facility and large leak on the bottom of the metal 55 gallon container. The drum was overpacked into an 851A2 salvage drum to contain the leak and offered to Norlite for proper disposal. Soil that was impacted was also cleaned up.      The drum leaked about half of its contents of mixed solvents due to the hole in the bottom of the drum.  The duration of release is anticipated to be about 60 minutes with about 200 pounds of material leaking. On 6/08/2021 the Veolia safety manager notified the National Response Center to report the spill (Report#1307227). The results of the investigation is that a drum had a hole in it due to sharp debris under the drum that was not cleaned when loading the containers into the trailer. The container was inspected prior to shipping and did not have any issues. The NYDEC was also notified of the spill and responded to it. They were notified around 5:45 PM by Veolia (Spill#2102181).
column169: The cause of a spill was a debris on the floor of a trailer where a 55 gallon drum was placed. The debris and drum were in the front corner of the trailer. While loading it and preparing it for transportation, employees did not clean the debris up. Veolia employees must continue to inspect trailers for debris prior to loading drums onto them. We also had a meeting on June 10, 2021 to review safety procedures and assuring proper housekeeping is done in trailers and at the facility. In addition, we reviewed the protocols for shipping drums to Norlite and also have implemented that drums doing to Norlite will be placed on pallets to prevent this from happening again as well as be safer for employees having to move the drums at the Norlite facility.    Veolia will continue to review the causes of spills with employees to prevent any further leaking of containers. In this particular case, the container was inspected and looked as if it was OK to transport as offered. During the investigation, it was discovered that the container was damaged when being transported across a rough road at the entrance to the Norlite facility. The spill was also reported to the customer/shipper and more care will be used in the future to prevent a similar issue from happening again.

column168: On 6/11/2021 at 12:25PM EST FRA Hazmat Inspector Kevin Cash in the CSXT Montgomery Terminal  discovered PROX36095, a residue tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas placarded with improper  stenciling. PROX36095 did not have NON ODORIZED LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS stenciling on both  sides. After further investigation it was found that the car was an undeclared hazmat shipment.  The car was placarded UN1075, but the billing showed the car was a clean & purged package. The  car was isolated and Targa Resources, Lisa Jo Meyers were notified. PROX36095 was confirmed to be  a residue hazmat package with non hazmat billing. The issue identified and corrective actions were  communicated to the shipper Lisa Jo Meyers and 713-584-1166. On June 25, 2021, at approximately 6:00 a.m. CDT, a tanker operated by Sully Transport (ST) was transferring jet fuel into an aboveground storage stank (AST) when jet fuel overfilled the tank due to unknown circumstances.  As a result, approximately 660 gallons of jet fuel released to the concrete surfaces of the runway, aged asphalt surfaces of a parking lot, inside nearby airplane hangar, surrounding soil surfaces of the before mentioned, a water filled ditch, and in a nearby private pond. A representative from National Interstate Insurance (NII) retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to provide an assessment. At approximately 7:30 p.m. CDT, a crew from ES arrived on-site. Their assessment noted sand deployed for site containment by local fire department personnel. ES deployed absorbent boom and pads for additional containment, then demobilized, scheduling to return the following day for continued action.  On June 26, 2021, a crew from ES returned to the site. The crew delineated the site and determined an area of approximately 100,000 square feet in need of remediation. The crew demobilized, scheduling to return at a later date for further corrective action.

column168: Phillips 66 loaded the four tank cars (GATX 231130, TILX 101963, TILX 101981, and TILX 101944) at its Wood River refinery with spent sulfuric acid and released them at approximately 7:11 am CT on 5/25/21.  NS then pulled the cars from the refinery and placed them at the Wilds Yard in Wood River.  At the time NS pulled the cars from Phillips 66 and placed them in the Wilds Yard they were not venting.  All four cars were spotted to the industry switch track and interchanged for pickup by Kansas City Southern Railroad (?KCS?) at 7:00 am CT on 5/27/21.  KCS did not arrive for pickup of the cars until 6/2/21. KCS hooked up to the cars in the afternoon of 6/2/21 and, in the process of releasing the brake system, discovered that GATX 231130 was venting.  KCS unhooked, pulled away, and the conductor requested medical assistance and was taken to a local hospital, but was not admitted.  The other three cars (TILX 101963, TILX101981 and TILX 101944) began venting on 6/3/21.  NS mobilized its hazardous materials incident response team to assist the Wood River Fire Department with emergency response on 6/2/21. Phillips 66?s fire department, Madison County Emergency Management/Madison County Hazmat, and the Wood River Police also responded. Remedial measures including water curtains and air scrubbing units were used to mitigate the release from 6/3/21 to 6/7/21.  On 6/7/21 and 6/8/21 responders replaced/repaired components of the pressure relief devices (?PRDs?) on the tank cars.  At 7:00 pm CT on 6/8/21 all four tank cars were moved back into the Phillips 66 refinery.  The tank cars began venting due to Phillips 66?s spent sulfuric acid undergoing a polymeric reaction, which created overpressurization that released through the PRDs on the four tank cars.

column168: Driver had stopped, when he returned to his vehicle conducting an inspection he noticed a leak coming from his trailer. He reported the incident to his supervisor and a response team was dispatched to mitigate the incident and clean-up the spill. Driver utilized the spill kit until the response team arrived. The response crew identified that the leak was a hole in the bottom of a drum, apparently a pallet nail had punctured the drum. The container when shipped had a weight of 127 pounds. It is estimated that the mixture weighed 7.2 lbs. so there was approximately 17.64 gallons. the response crew estimated they recovered 16 gallons during their clean-up.
column169: Employees were made aware of the incident and the cause of the incident and have been advised to inspect pallets for nails sticking up and to hammer protruding nails.

column168: Customer baggage was in process of screened by TSA. During secondary inspection, the TSA agent came in contact with a caustic substance that had leaked within the customer's bag. Agent complained of possible burns to hands. Taken to hospital as precaution and subsequently released. A separate Delta agent went to the bag room to retrieve the items for reporting and experienced the same physical reaction. Delta agent was also taken to hospital for treatment and released. Clean Harbors activated for retrieval and securing of customer baggage. Field tests indicate a pH level of 11 and higher. Physical inspection indicated a caustic substance (UN 1823) that had leaked out of an internal Pelican-style case. Baggage was wrapped and placed in 30-gallon poly drum for further storage and FAA inspection.

column168: On July 12, 2021 at 0655 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics about a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a broken cap Hydrochloric Acid Solution (Hazardous - UN1789) was released from a 300 gallon poly tote. The caller requested a contractor to inspect the lid to see if it only requires replacement or to advise if product needs to be transferred into a new tote due to damages to the tote. ERTS dispatched Patriot Environmental to conduct cleanup operations. On July 14, 2021 at 1045 EST, Patriot arrived onsite and confirmed 1 cup of product released to the top of the tote and dried there. The contractor stated the tote cap was inspected and found to be very loose but not damaged. The crew wiped down the impacted area of the tote with soda ash and water solution and re-tighten the cap. They then got a forklift to perform a slosh test to confirm security. Once confirmed there would be no more release the crew left site. The tote and a 5 gallon pail of waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 06/10/2021, at 0205 hours, personnel in the CSXT Woodburne Yard discovered TILX 111588, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2021-0610-00023). Marion Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found Hydrochloric Acid adjacent to the pressure relief device. Upon further inspection, all other service equipment was properly secured, and 60 psig was observed via accessing the vapor valve. The pressure was relieved from the car, and the fill port was open and liquid product was observed approximately 6 inches above the shell of the tank car. This confirmed the tank car was offered in transportation without the required outage. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Doug Nestler of Univar, phone 408-221-4964. Contractor personnel secured the car, cleaned and neutralized all spilled material and arranged to have product unloaded from the car. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required?  Cause Code: 419 NARRI: 100

column168: TILX 111371 located on outbound H-VBTVAW1-26 on 103 track leaked approx. 4-5 gallons of HCL sides of tank car and ballast and rails. US Ecology did assessment and inspected car. column168: PERLOADER NOTICE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING CALLED FOR SUPERVISOR RESPONDER WAS CALLED

• Driver was unloading AC-103 to tank CP01 at Sunopta in Alexandria, Mn • The customer fill line is vertical.  The hook up is 4 feet off the ground, goes up another 4 feet, then over 25 feet, then up another 8 feet and the elbow goes in to a building. • Driver was following protocols when uncapping their line.  He was uncapping the fill line away from him.  He released one of the camlock ears slowly and as he started to remove the cap product sprayed out like it was under pressure and he quickly locked that camlock back down.  1-2 cups released.   o Presumably this residue that was in the line was under pressure from sitting in the heat.   • He immediately started showering down as all his PPE was covered with these droplets including his hard hat and face shield.  He believes as he was taking off his PPE that it rinsed off his hard hat on to his chest, ran down to his stomach, then must have transferred to his bibs and impacted his ankle.  Nothing else in between was impacted.  None of this was known on the initial shower.   • Driver then was told that the last delivery the tank was filled to capacity and they had to do a wet break and is likely how some product was in the line.  However, my challenge to that is that the fill line is vertical with no shut off so when that last one delivered anything in the line should have come out.  Perhaps with the 25 feet of horizontal piping it took some time for that to get down to the connection point.   • That said, he felt comfortable popping the cap off in to his bucket this time around and roughly ½ cup came out (not under pressure this time) in to his bucket.   • As they started unloading he noticed some burning sensation and told the plant who told him he could shower again which he did with soap.  Afterwards now he feels fine, just some redness on the impacted areas. Triage Now was notified and determined that he didn't need to go in unless his symptoms got worse.  • He finished that unload and the next one before calling in which I coached him on.  He felt because the plant was ready to continue and he felt ok that he could report it afterwards.  I told him that we didn’t want him making that determination especially after the shock of having it happen isn’t the best time to be making any self-diagnosis.  He agrees that with that mentality.   • He did have on all the correct PPE at the time of the incident  (chemical suit, chemical boots, chemical gloves, hard hat, face shield, goggles.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Release of 56 MMBTU.  After filling the unit and compression was over. The heat of compression continued in the cylinders per thermodynamic law. The fill ended at 4250 psig. Pressure rose to 4400 psig and the relief set for 4500 psig released.  Weather was humid and hot, overcast, high 80's.  The relief was to vent in case of an overfill event. The relief lifted 100 psig early.  Valves on the individual tank cylinders were closed to stop the unplanned vent.  Duration: 5 min  The PRV is within its 5 year recertification window and compliant to the DOT SP.
column169: The relief will be tested.  This is a rare failure and do not see it becoming a systemic problem.  All reliefs are tested every 5 years per recertification.  The trailer systems acted as designed except 100 psig earlier.  We have reduced fill pressure to 4100 psig in summer operation. As we are assessing failure.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: Driver picked up the IBC container from the generator site at 0717 on 6/28/2021.  Driver inspected containers prior to shipment, loaded them onto truck, and strapped them down. Driver had several other stops that day between 1000 and 1430.  Driver inspected final load before leaving from his last stop for the day.  On the way back to his office, upon approaching southbound scales driver was pulled in to scale-house  for an inspection.  It was then discovered the tote was leaking.  Fire department was called to assist. They determined it to be a leaking valve on the IBC container.  The valve could not be tightened any further due to damage on the inside of the IBC container.    Our internal emergency services team was called out to assist in spill clean up and pumping out the  damaged IBC. The driver was onsite with the truck from 1530 to 2330 at which point the driver had been given clearance to store the truck at the northbound scales overnight and find a conveyance to get him home for the night.
column169: Management Team Investigation concluded the spill was not driver error.   We did determine, for unknown reasons, the contents of the tote reacted during transport.   Additionally, Fremont FD Hazmat team identified a potential issue with the valve gasket.   Motor Carrier has expired profile until we have sampled and know the constituents.   Tote to be inspected so as to identify a potential compromised valve.   Account Manager to confer with customer in order to convey the need for compliant containers. San Jose management team to provide summaries of notification to customer regarding their totes.    . Drivers continue to diligently inspect all containers prior to loading so as to ensure container compliance.

JUG THAT WAS DAMAGED HAD ABOUR 40% OF ITS CONTENTS SPILLED OUT INTO THE BIN. ANY & ALL PPE USED TO CLEAN UP AND INVESTIGATE PACKAGE HAS AND WILL CONTINUE TO BE STORED IN BIN WITH PACKAGE, INSIDE OF THE HAZMAT CAGE WHILE WE AWAIT DISPOSITION. DescribePack: CAP/CLOSURE WAS THE POINT OF FAILURE. CANNOT VISIBLY MAKE OUT THE CRACK, BUT EVEN WHEN CAP IS TIGHTENED THE JUG STILL LEAKS. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED TO A BIN AND INTO THE HAZMAT CAGE

SequenceEvent: BOX WAS FOUND ALREADY BAGGED AND IN A BIN TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. DURING THE INVESTIGATION I FOUND ONE OF FOUR 1 GALLON JUGS OF 95% REAGENT ALCOHOL HAD A LOOSE CAP AND ABOUT HALF OF THE CONTENTS SPILLED EXTERNALLY INTO THE BAG & BIN. CAP WAS ABLE TO BE TIGHTENED, WHICH DID MITIGATE THE LEAK COMPLETELY. ALL PPE, CLEANING SUPPLIES, PACKAGE, & BIN WILL CONTINUE TO BE STORED IN THE HAZMAT CAGE, WHILE WE AWAIT DISPOSITION. DescribePack: CAP/CLOSURE WAS LOOSE DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY BAGGED, MOVED TO A BIN, AND THEN INTO THE HAZMATE CAGE FOR SAFE STORAGE.

column168: At 1224 ET XPO Logistics called to report a 2 quart release of UN1044 "K-GUARD" from a 24 pound fire extinguisher impacting the trailer floor. The fire extinguisher was crushed in transit.  ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller who felt comfortable cleaning up the release. Terminal personnel donned PPE and cleaned the product with oil dri, the damaged container and cleanup debris was placed into a 10 gallon metal drum and staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: 1624 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal (XDE) contacted ERTS to report a UN1263 cargo release that occurred over the road. It was reported that a 55 gallon metal drum containing flammable paint was discovered leaking in the trailer due to the customer puncturing the drum with a forklift, releasing a total of 10 gallons of the product to the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to the site to conduct cleanup activities. At 1845 EST, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 25 gallons of product released to a 6' x 10' area of the concrete lot and a 40' x 8' area of the trailer floor. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected. The damaged drum was placed into a 95 gallon poly overpack. The spent absorbents and cleanup debris were containerized into (1) 55 gallon poly and (3) 55 gallon metal drums. All waste was transported to the XPO Logistics Terminal located in Romulus, MI for terminal personnel to manage.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Circle K contacted ERTS regarding an 80 gallon gasoline release that occurred during unloading. Miguel stated the release impacted concrete only and the local Fire Department responded to the site and sprayed foam on the impacted areas. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor (OMI Inc) for response and remedial operations. OMI arrived on site and confirmed an estimated 80 gallons of gasoline released to a concrete area measuring 15' x 15'. OMI stated the release impacted a nearby drain. OMI confirmed they will flush the drain and work the impacted area with push brooms to remove the free standing gasoline. OMI personnel have utilized the vacuum truck to flush the drain and to collect the foam deployed by the fire department. OMI personnel have completed the cleanup. All of the gasoline, impacted water and foam was collected in the vacuum truck. An additional 55-gallon drum of absorbent pads was also generated. All waste was taken off site for pending disposal.

column168: Driver was standing outside of the truck by the pump while product was being unloaded, the plant personnel had hooked the hose to their containment tank and told Mr. Walker they would radio him over the loud speaker in the plant as to when the pump needed to be shut off. He never heard anything over the speaker, but one of the plant employees came running to him and told him to shut the pump off, product was coming out of the tank at the top. They told the driver the over flow valve to the secondary tank was shut and it should have been opened, and that is what caused about 10 gallons to over flow out of the top of the tank. ll.

column168: On 06/30/2021 This shipment was discovered to contain hidden dangerous goods during the physical inspection process at yhe DHL BKL service center, 653 East 56th St. Brooklyn, NY 11203 Transportation by road has been confirmed.

The driver was driving south-bound on HWY 55 South when his tote fell off the trailer due to a broken strap in the middle of a curve near mile marker 488. The force of the tote falling off the truck caused the body to burst releasing all the contents of the package. Upon discovery of the release, inert material was used to absorb and contain the liquid. TAS Environmental was then contacted and requested to provide emergency response services. A crew was dispatched to the location and arrived about 17 hours after the incident occurred. The crew used a skid steer loader to scrape the top layer of impacted soil and absorbent. All waste generated was removed from the site and staged for disposal.
column169: In order to prevent an incident like this from happening again, our company has improved operating procedures in the following ways. Two straps rather than one are used per tote and are placed on the outside edge rather than the middle. This puts less stress on each strap, and it prevents the tote from buckling under tension and causing the straps to move from side to side. Strap protectors will, also, be used to provide an additional layer of protection against any edges that might cause wear. Additionally, our stock of backup straps was increased to ensure worn ones can always be immediately replaced.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On June 15, 2021, at 0215 hours, an odor was reported emanating from the Kansas City Southern Railway(KCS) Rosebluff Yard in Westlake, LA. The source of the odor was unknown at the time of initial report. The KCS Environmental& Hazmat Department mobilized a railroad qualified response contractor to investigate the odor. Upon arrival, the response contractor Identified residue tank car UTLX 208596(PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S., UN1268, Haz Class 3, PG I) as the source of the odor. The release was emanatlng from the recloslng pressure relief device(PRD). The PRD's O-Rings were in poor condition, thus allowing vapor to escape. Estimated release Is 0.01 gallon. New O-Rings were installed. The remaining closures, fittings and valves were checked for securement and after verifying the car was secure, UTLX 208595 was released. Shipper is responsible for OTMA to shop for PRD requalificatlon. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered In this package Is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can caus6 personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adJacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper Is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

AN FRA HAZMAT INSPECTION TOOK PLACE IN JANESVILLE, WI ON 6/27/21 BY INSPECTOR PERKINS IN WHICH IT WAS NOTED THAT 8 MANWAY COVER BOLT NUTS WERE NOT TIGHTENED DOWN ON UTLX 213039. DURING THIS PROCESS THE CAR WAS DEEMED UNSHIPPABLE UNTIL NUTS WERE TIGHTENED DOWN AND MUSTBE SET OUT FROM THE TRAIN. WHILE THE SWITCHING OPERATION BEGAN TO SET THE CAR OUT FOR REPAIR, THE TANK BEGAN TO SLOSH CAUSING ETHANOL TO LEAK OUT OF THE MANWAY COVER DOWN THE SIDE OF THE RAILCAR. THE RELEASE WAS ONLY FOR A SHORT PERIOD IN WHICH THE TANK SLOSHING SUBSIDED. THE ETHANOL BEGAN TO EVAPORATE AS IT TRCIKLED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR. IT IS UNCERTAIN AS TO THE THE AMOUNT RELEASED BUT LESS THAN A GALLON WOULD BE ACCURATE. BADGER STATE ETHANOL CAME IN AT 06:00 6/28/21 TO TIGHTEN THE NUTS DOWN ON UTLX 213039.

column168: While offtoading and reloading a 10-Day trailer at the 10-Day Dock, the individual operating the forklift on the dock to load totes approached a tote containing 75% Phosphoric Acid Solution from the side to lift the tote. The forks of the forklift were tilted upwards roughly 3-5 inches instead of being flat. The point of the left fork punctured the poly bladder of the tote. This slit caused acid to leak out of the tote. The slit was 1-3 inches above the base of the tote, 1-3 inches above the 1 st metal ring around the bottom of the tote that sits on the base, and bent the metal framing that runs diagonally in the middle of the tote. The slit allowed for 2 streams of acid to leak from the tote. The 11ow pressure of the release was about equivalent to a drinking fountain. All individuals working on the 10-Day clock stopped work, notified project manager who was still at the facility, and created a barrier with oil dry around the damaged tote to contain the release enough for someone to employ sausage boom. Boom was then placed around approximately 15ft x 12ft area of concrete on the dock. A pump was utilized to pump the product out of the damaged tote into a new, compatible tote with the same specs as the damaged tote. Soda ash was used to neutralize the leaked phosphoric acid on the concrete. Personnel utilized properly rated tyvek suits with boot covers, properly rated gloves, and respirators to remove the material. Soda ash was poured onto the concrete and slowly mixed in with the acid to neutralize the pH and solidify the liquid. The dean up debris was scraped and shoveled into 55 gallon poly drums as well as all used pig pads, boom, and PPE. No more than 50 gallons of acid leaked from the damaged tote. The hole in the tote was less than one inch in' depth and approximately 2.5 inches in diameter. The leak did not go outside of the 15ft x 12ft area and was contained to just the concrete on the 10-Day dock. No injuries occurred from the release. The release was contained within 15 minutes of the tote being damaged. Material was repacked within 30 min. Spill
column169: covered forklift safety and spill response procedures and included all personnel of the Technical Services Department out of the Wood River office. A forklift training refresher course will help prevent future incidents of this type. This material shipped with waste code D002(RQ= 100 lbs.). Phosphoric Acid Solution(75%) weighs about 13.1 lbs/gallon. That said, the 50 gallons that leaked weighs about 655 lbs., which is over the RQ for this material. However, this event is exempt from RQ reporting as the material did not enter environment(the material leaked onto concrete and was contained fully within 15 minutes). Reporting is also excluded under the definition of'Release' at 40 CFR 302.3. Finally, EPCRA also exempts this release under 40 CFR 355.31(a) as there was no exposure beyond the boundaries of the facility.

column42: ETHYLENE OXIDE OR ETHYLENE OXIDE WITH NITROGEN UP TO A TOTAL PRESSURE OF 1MPA (10 BAR) AT 50 DEGREES C
column168: RAILCAR TILX40188 WAS CONNECTED TO THE UNLOADING FACILITY FOR SAMPLING PURPOSES. DURING PRESSURIZATION TO OBTAIN SAMPLE, A LEAK WAS DETECTED AT APPROXIMATELY 35 PSI. PRESSURIZATION STOPPED AND CAR WAS VENTED TO FLARE SYSTEM. PRESSURE REDUCED TO 13 PSI AND LEAK STOPPED. PRESSURE FURTHER REDUCED TO 10 PSI. CAR MONITORED EVERY 30 MINUTES WITH NO EMISSIONS DETECTABLE. AFTER 27 HOURS, FUGITIVE VAPOR DETECTED AND DETERMINED TO BE FROM PINHOLE LEAK ON PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE O-RING. MIDLAND KIT APPLIED TO PRV AND CAR SAFELY UNLOADED AND DEPRESSURIZED. COORDINATING WITH CAR LESSOR/OWNER TO HAVE PRV REPAIRED AND DETERMINE CAUSE OF O-RING FAILURE. CALCULATED LEAK QUANTITY AS 23 LB.

On 6/4/2021 at approximately 0800, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee # 986811 at the RKW station, reporting a corrosive spill. While offloading an aircraft, the agent noticed a that a shipment appeared stained on the bottom of the box. Furthermore, several packages stacked underneath the shipment that had stains that were a similar color. Further investigation revealed that, among other items, the original package contained a bottle of Drano drain cleaner. The bottle of Drano appeared to have ruptured, completely spilling in the box. The package did not the appropriate markings, labeling, packaging, or paperwork required for shipping dangerous goods. The empty bottle was sent for disposal and the remining items in the shipment were cleaned and transport further to the consignee.

The shipment was discovered leaking during sort operations. The outer packaging was a FedEx padded pack (plastic bag), Inner contents : 1 plastic container @ 4L of Advanced Nutrients, PH-UP. The package was placed in a salvage drum and held for FAA investigation.
PACKAGE WAS FOUND AS A LEAKER. THE DECISION TREE WAS USED TO BRING THE PACKAGE BACK TO THE DMP WHERE IT WAS DESCOVERED TO BE A SUSPECTED UNDECLARED HAZMAT.

Bulk shipment consisting of 15 plastic jerricans of UN1197 arrived at location in Guangzhou, CN. During offload it was seen one package of the 15 had developed a leak during transit and an estimated 500ml escaped from the can. Package was placed in a steel salvage container and shipper was contacted for retrieval.

column168: On June 7th, 2021 a JCI Jones Driver was on-site at the American Water Greenwood, IN Marlin WTF to deliver 1900 US gallons of Sodium Hypochlorite. While unloading into the customer storage tanks the female end on the hose connected directly to the tank began to leak. The driver quickly reacted to shutoff the tanker and stop the flow of product into the tank. Once shutoff the estimated amount spilled was 5-8 gallons that was then cleaned up by the Greenwood facility team. Upon further investigation, the end of the connected hose had a crack in the fitting that allowed the Sodium Hypochlorite to leak out once pressurized.
column169: All hose were inspected for each tanker onsite at JCI Jones Chemicals in Beech Grove, IN. All drivers discussed and reviewed both pre-trip and post-trip requirements to ensure equipment meets the quality needed for deliveries. The JCI Jones Chemicals Standard Operating Procedure for Loading and Unloading Tankers was reviewed and discussed with all personnel that may be involved in the process for JCI Jones Beech Grove.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: This shipment was found to be leaking during the sort. Approximately 60 mL had leaked and burned through the box. The manufacturer's Safety Data Sheet indicates the identification/classification of UN 1789, Hydrochloric Acid, class 8 corrosive material Packing Group II. As the shipper did not offer the shipment with any DG markings, DG labels nor with a shipper's declaration it is undeclared or hidden DG. Standard spill cleanup procedures were followed. The FAA was notified via email and photos sent. The shipment was held for FAA  until they released it.

On 6/10/2021 at approximately 0930, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee # 208260, reporting an undeclared toxic shipment. Per the agent, A shipment declared as Naphthoxyacetic Acid was tested by US Customs and found to been Abamectin substance, a highly Toxic described also in an SDS-UN2811, Class 6 . 1PKG I Numerous attempts to contact Consignee/Shipper so far failed. The shipper contacted the Accounts Department and requested disposal for the shipment, however, the shipment is being held, pending FAA investigation.
